<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
[Disclaimer: This started out as a reply to another thread, but quickly took on a life of its own.  I submit it for your perusal, I will warn you ahead of time, it is very long...]<P>The following is my own personal opinion.  I seek not to speak for anyone else, nor do I make any claims to know everything there is to know about this class.  It is up to the individual to take from it what he or she will..and as always, feel free to agree or disagree...<P>To date, I have played 4 different Sorcerers on the live servers, (and a couple of variants in beta, but sorcerers were so different then that I hardly even mention that anymore).  And after each of the first three I learned a little bit more about how I like to play my Sorcerer, and how best to use the tools I have at my disposal along the way.  What I have arrived at is a template, or spec progression, that suits my own personal taste to a tee.  It allows me to do all the things I enjoy doing, and has proven to be enough fun that I can say with assuredness that this is the template I will take out to 50.  <P>In a nutshell, I will be spending my spec points relatively evenly between Matter and Mind with the goal of hitting the "charm milestones" along the way.  What that means is making sure I get the charm that will allow me yellow pets just as the previous spell phases out.  Any excess points will be placed into body.  At level 50 I will have the following spec levels: Matter:35, Body:22, Mind:34.  I can hear the collective gasp of disbelief from all those body spec'ed sorcerers out there so I will share some of the reasons why I have arrived at this rather uncommon template, and why it fits the way I like to play so well.<P>I will start with the given, having a 2/3+ spec level in Mind allows me the ability to not only bring to a group the traditional abilities one would associate with a Sorcerer, but also do them well.  At level 50 I will have the second highest ranged AE Mez and by hitting the "charm milestones" I will ensure that I have even con pets at my disposal all along the way, including level 50 pets.<P>With only a slight focus in body, I primarily rely on the base line drain for fast damage.  The spec progression I plan calls for an increased emphasis on body in later levels, right at the time I hit the main RvR and right when a tightening of the damage variance of the base-line drains will be most needed.  At level 50, I will have a 22 in body, but with items I can pull that up to the low to mid 30's which will ensure that the damage variance of the drain, though still greater than the norm, would still be very livable for me.<P>Which brings me to matter and the big question, why on earth do you make matter a primary spec?  To answer that, I will offer some examples of how I have used the dots to full effect.  In clerk groups what I would typically do, if I was the primary crowd controller, is allow the puller to do his thing and cast an AE mez on the incoming group.  Assuming they stragglers were immobilized, I would then assist on the tank and cast either my base-line or spec-line DoT.  The determining factor between the two would be how tank heavy our group was, and the level of damage output I expected from who we had available.  The trick is to do damage and not draw aggro.  So in cases where I expected high damage output from our tanks, I would cast the base-line DoT because its damage occurs over 4 pulses for a higher amount each pulse.  The pulses were doing between high 50's and low 60's each time.  My focus in matter ensured that the damage variance was very minimal...which in turn meant that, assuming the mob lived 4 pulses, I was contributing a guaranteed 200+ points of damage to the mob.  In cases where I didn't think the tanks could dish out damage fast enough to hold the aggro against my base-line DoT, I would use the spec DoT because it pulses 6 times at a lower amount each time.  It works out to be about the same amount of damage in the end which in this case is a good thing (though this is also one of the primary things I feel should be fixed with the matter spec track..but thats another post...).  The real beauty of it is the fact that while the DoT was ticking, I was absolutely free to keep my eyes on the remaining mezzed mobs and re-mez if necessary.  In short, the fire and forget property of DoTs allows me spend more time focussing on keeping mobs immobilized, while at the same time contributing to the damage output of the group.  I used this technique to great effect in Darkness Falls as well. When I was soloing, I would use the very same tactic with the exception that my pet was the tank.  I would pull with debuffs, and send my pet in to build aggro.  Once engaged, I make the assessment of whether I should cast the base-line or spec line Dot.  Typically against yellow and lower, I would use the Base-line DoT...against Oranges, I would use the spec DoT.  I would then time my drains so as not to draw the aggro.  And yes, I consistently would solo oranges without a second thought...and provided I had a source of pets nearby (because against an orange the pet does take quite a beating) I could do them in fairly rapid succession.  <P>In RvR things require a different set of tactics, however.  In cases where I was in a group and we had the spell initiative (i.e. either the opposing group ran into our spell casting distance, or we surpised them and ran into theirs) and I scored a quickcast AE Mez, I followed pretty much the same tactics as above....DoT'ing and focussing on keeping the others immobilized.  (Incidentally, these were the rare times when I would get noticeable RP, but were also the least fun...).  In cases where it was more of a skirmish in addition to trying to help out the tanks with damage output, I would be focussed on finding opposing spell casters and archers and keeping them interrupted or occupied, often these times I would die very quickly because getting them into my spell casting distance meant I had just walked into theirs and I would see my "bolt of death" heading right for me.  (Incidently I would get very little if any RP from these type of chaotic skirmishes...but the successes I had and the RP gained I savored much more...not to mention I had by far, the most fun in these type of encounters).  <BR> <BR>The point to all of this, is that I spec primarily in matter...by choice.  Not out of a sense of self-punishment, and not for lack of knowledge of the pros and cons of what I gain or give up.  I enjoy it, and wouldn't change it for the world.  Make of that what you will....<P>--------------------<P>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<BR>Myrcil the Briton Matter Sorcerer<BR>Member of the Furious Pantaloons<BR>Galahad Server<BR>Member of the Sorcerer Testing Team in Beta<BR>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<P>"Who could ever calculate the path of a molecule?<BR>How do we know that the creations of worlds are not determined by falling grains of sand?"<BR>  --Victor Hugo, Les Miserables
</FONT>
