<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Before this gets characterized as an endorsement for everyone to re-roll as matter spec sorcerers, I figured I would dig through and repost my suggestion for fixing the school of matter.<P>You can find the full thread at the following:<BR> <A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic&f=21&t=000624" TARGET=_blank>http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic&f=21&t=000624</A> <P>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<BR>There are some serious problems with the matter base and spec lines.  What I am going to try and do is deal with these problems in a rational manner so that hopefully someone will see the wisdom and do something to fix it…<P>The most glaring flaw in the design of the matter line is the scaling of the damages for the base-line versus spec-line DoT's.  The Damage over time spells are the meat of the Matter school and comprise the primary attack option for someone spending spec points in matter.  A major factor that stands in stark opposition to a DoT's usefulness is the fact that often fights do not last long enough for a DoT to do it's full damage.  This is a serious problem, but one that requires a reworking of the core dynamics of the game, and that, in turn, is not something I would feel comfortable having the developers muck with at this point.  I would suggest that our first concern should be to get our spells to work well and make sense first…(jeeez, this is such déjà vu from beta, this game is live, right?)<P>So, that having been said, lets examine the mess that is the school of matter twisting.  As I mentioned, DoTs are it's bread and butter.  But the setup, as it stands now, makes very little sense.  For starters, one of the differences between the base and spec DoTs is the fact that a base-line DoT will pulse 4 times while the spec DoT will pulse 6 times. This is an aspect I really do not have a problem with.  In fact, I think it is a nice way to setup the difference between the two and lays the foundation to really adding an incentive for the spec dot.  It’s the analysis of how the developers implemented the spells given this foundation that really begs the question, what were they thinking? <P>Keep in mind this is just base damage.  A lot is factored into how much the the spell will actually pulse for.  It may perform better or worse for you depending on how many (if any) spec points you have placed into matter.  <P>Base-line DoT vs Spec-line DoT<BR>Lvl: 1    BaseDmg: 2  <BR>Lvl: 2    BaseDmg: 4 <BR>Lvl: 3    BaseDmg: 6    SpecLvl: 3    SpecDmg: 6  <BR>Lvl: 5    BaseDmg: 9    SpecLvl: 5    SpecDmg: 9<BR>Lvl: 7    BaseDmg: 13    SpecLvl: 7    SpecDmg: 13<BR>Lvl: 10    BaseDmg: 17    SpecLvl: 10    SpecDmg: 17    <BR>Lvl: 13    BaseDmg: 23    SpecLvl: 13    SpecDmg: 23    <BR>Lvl: 16    BaseDmg: 29    SpecLvl: 16    SpecDmg: 29<BR>Lvl: 21    BaseDmg: 37    SpecLvl: 21    SpecDmg: 37<BR>Lvl: 27    BaseDmg: 49    SpecLvl: 27    SpecDmg: 49<BR>Lvl: 35    BaseDmg: 63    SpecLvl: 35    SpecDmg: 63<BR>Lvl: 44    BaseDmg: 79    SpecLvl: 44    SpecDmg: 79<BR>Lvl: 50                              SpecLvl: 50    SpecDmg: 89<P>So, okay, I formatted the above list to illustrate a point.  According to all the testing I did in Beta (and believe me, I did tons) the same set of circumstances effect both the base and spec DoTs.  What that means is that all other things remaining equal, at level 10, assuming you full spec in matter, your base line DoT will pulse for the same average damage over a period of time as your spec line DoT at a level 10 spec.  The difference being your spec line DoT will pulse twice more than your base DoT.  But what are the ramifications of this setup?  Well what it amounts to is that the only way to ensure that your spec DoT will be more effective (i.e. Do more damage) than your base DoT will be to full spec all the way through.<P>In a word, that setup is ridiculous.  The same person who full specs in matter, and has the distinguished honor of having a spec dot that is better than his base dot will also have just sealed the door on having an equal level pet or any significant AoE mez…two important tools in Sorcerers RvR arsenal.  That same person would have also sealed the door on any meaningful DD as well as ensure that the damage for his drains will be flakey to say the least.  It does not surprise me in the least that almost no one specs in matter currently. Why would anyone who has all the facts want to, honestly?<P>Well, okay, enough gloom and doom.  I am going to offer 2 scenarios that may work to improve the viability of our DoTs and in turn make the Matter school more appealing.<P>Scenario 1: Re-scale the spec line DoTs<BR>Basically, one way that could fix things is to scale the Spec DoT base damage in such a way as to make it so that someone 2/3rds spec'ing (supposedly the target level) will have a spec dot with equal base damage as the base-line DoT.  Simply put….someone at level 24 with 2/3rds spec in Matter (a spec level of 16)  would have access to the 21st level base-line dot with a base damage of 37….the level 16 spec-line DoT should have a base damage of 37 also.  The same would hold true all the way through.  But there is a draw-back to this scenario.  What it would mean is that someone full-speccing in matter would then have a spec line DoT that has the potential to do almost un-balancing damage.  But is that really a bad thing?  They are giving up the possibility to have an even level pet.  They are accepting the fact that their Drains will do a very wide range of damage.  I believe there are enough balancing factors in place to warrant at least a little investigation into whether this would work or not..<P>Scenario 2: Make the Spec line DoT AoE<BR>This is the less invasive and more likely of the two scenarios I propose.  It amounts to a band-aid fix that at least addresses the obvious problem of the spec line spell not being enough of an incentive to spec in matter.  It does have some advantages over the current setup, however.  For example, take a sorcerer at level 27 who 2/3rd specs in matter (spec level of 18).  They would have the level 27 base line DoT with a base damage of 49 and the level 16 spec DoT with a base damage of 29.  Now, take a hypothetical encounter where the sorcerer, casting this AoE spec DoT, manages to stick it on 2 enemies.  The net base damage per pulse for that spell in that encounter would effectively become 58.  Maybe he gets 3 in the AoE.  It then effectively becomes 87.  Now, I know some of you are thinking why on earth would a sorcerer in his or her right mind want to stick a dot on 3 monsters and draw agro…isn’t that suicide? Perhaps, but that’s not where this spell would truly shine.  Imagine it's RvR and your level 45 and you 2/3rd spec'ed in matter.  You would have a spec level of 30.  Those of you who have spec'ed 2/3rds in mind, how many have you caught in an AoE mez?….3, 5, 7?  Imagine in the chaos that it was a DoT…you would be actively doing damage to all 7 for 6 pulses.  Heck, imagine turning around and tossing an AoE dot into another group of people…now how many are you actively effecting?  The balancing factor here is that at a spec level of 30 you would only have access to a spec dot with a base damage of 49.  Of course, level is factored into the equation that determines how much the spell will actually pulse for….but it certainly isn't bolt damage.  The fact that you would do the damage to potentially lots of people are what would make it useful.  <BR>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<P>Again, I agree Matter is broken....above is my suggestion on how to fix it. And I still enjoy my choice in making matter a primary spec...<P>--------------------<P>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<BR>Myrcil the Briton Matter Sorcerer<BR>Member of the Furious Pantaloons<BR>Galahad Server<BR>Member of the Sorcerer Testing Team in Beta<BR>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<P>"Who could ever calculate the path of a molecule?<BR>How do we know that the creations of worlds are not determined by falling grains of sand?"<BR>  --Victor Hugo, Les Miserables
</FONT>
