<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
There are plenty of debates as to effectiveness and efficiency, but DoTs are just a different playstyle.  Jenlei enjoys it, and so much the better I say.  More diversity!<P>A couple of points in arguement for DoTs, there's a couple prime uses...<P>First, I find them to be *very* pro-agro-management.  It's true that a Sorcerer can chain-cast about 4 DDs in the same power amount of one DoT, and do twice as much damage.  That's great, but in some instances, that's a *bad* thing.  See, DoTs allow you to sprinkle damage...doing four DDs for twice the damage will anger the Mob at you, which is a bad thing.  DoTs add your own extra bit of damage without worry of removing agro from the tanks (any tank that can't hit for 200 damage in the timeframe of 4-6 ticks shouldn't be whacking at the mob, they should be hitting grass snakes to practice more, or get a new sword instead of the wooden one they're using).  Now, there's the issue about amnesia: when the beast gets on the Cleric, the normal thing is either confuse it off (drastic), or wipe it's memory so the next hit by the fighters will redraw agro, right?  Well, when a DoT is on there, true, timing could make it so *you* are the next one who draws agro.  But consider this:  that one zap by the DoT is about 50 damage, right?  Hopefully one of the multiple fighters on the beast should be able to hit for more than 50 damage.  Mercenaries specifically hit very fast, so between that and Bladeturn, it seems like it's at least possible to avoid the nasty situation.<P>Second, and *very* important....DoTs are effective in RvR specifically against casters.  It interrupts them profusely, meaning they can only use their quickcast to get anything off.  So, in a battle, DoTs *can* be effective. <P>Now, someone asks, "Why not just DD the caster to death?"  Well, it depends on what you want to do in the fight.....say you have about 10 seconds to work before you die (yes, we die fast, as if anyone needs to learn that *grin*).  In that ten seconds, you can DD one caster to death and take him out of the fight, or you can apply about 3-4 DoTs to 3-4 different casters and keep all 3-4 of them unable to cast for however long the DoTs last.<P>(Note: I haven't tried this before.  Heh.  So I'm theorizing with what I know of how DoTs work.  Those who practice it, can you verify this?  Is there space between ticks when a caster can get a spell off?  Or is the space just small enough that it will always interrupt the caster?)
</FONT>
